All Implemented Interfaces:
java.awt.event.ActionListener, java.awt.event.ContainerListener, java.awt.event.KeyListener, java.awt.event.MouseListener, java.awt.image.ImageObserver, java.awt.MenuContainer, java.io.Serializable, java.util.EventListener, javax.accessibility.Accessible, javax.swing.RootPaneContainer, javax.swing.WindowConstants
public class JSTableDialog
extends JSDialog
implements java.awt.event.ActionListener, java.awt.event.KeyListener, java.awt.event.MouseListener, java.awt.event.ContainerListener

JSTableDialog is a class which allows a JSTable to be placed into a dialog along with a customisable set of JButtons. The dialog is modal, which allows it to wait for user input, such as selecting a row of the table, before continuing. ActionListeners, KeyListeners and MouseListeners for the table are handled automatically. The dialog's size changes dynamically when the row count or row height of the table changes so that as many rows as possible can be displayed at once.

Version:
1.0.3

JSTableDialog

public JSTableDialog(java.lang.String title,
                     java.lang.String[] headings,
                     java.lang.String[] buttonLabels,
                     int rows)
Creates a JSTableDialog with a fully customisable set of buttons. There is no limit to the number of buttons that can be used, but a limit of around five is recommended.

Parameters:
title - the title to display above the table.
headings - the headings for the table.
buttonLabels - an array of strings to be used for button labels.
rows - the initial number of rows for the table.
